===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} – a kind of agricultural tool used for tilling the fields and removing weeds ({{zh-ref|Guo, 1931}}; {{zh-ref|Qiu, 1992}}), possibly made of a kind of large clam {{och-l|蜃}} ({{zh-ref|Guo, 1931}}).

Alternatively, it could be a {{liushu|p|nocap=1}} of a person holding onto a cliff – original character of {{och-l|振|to hold up}} ({{zh-ref|Shang, 1983}}).

===Etymology===
; “to vibrate”
: Related to {{och-l|震|to shake}} and {{och-l|振|to excite}}, from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*dar ~ d(u/i)r||to tremble; to shiver}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

; “fifth earthly branch”
: {{zh-ref|Norman (1985)}} suggests that it is from {{der|zh|aav}}; compare {{cog|aav-pro|*tlan||python}}, whence {{cog|vi|trăn}}, {{cog|km|ថ្លាន់}}, {{cog|mnw|ကၠန်|tr=klɔn}}. However, {{zh-ref|Ferlus (2013)}} points to reconstructions like ''*dər'' (Baxter & Sagart) and ''*ᴸdzɨr'' (Ferlus) and remarks that those do not match any animal's name in {{w|Mainland Southeast Asia linguistic area|Mainland Southeast Asian (MSEA)}} languages. Therefore, {{lang|zh|辰}} might have been associated arbitrarily with the [[dragon]] ({{zh-l|*龍}}).
:{{zh-ref|Smith (2011)}} agrees with the proposal (e.g. by {{zh-ref|Guo, 1931}}) that {{och-l|辰|tr=dən}} initially depicted an agricultural implement made from clams' shells and was the original form of {{och-l|蜃|tr=dəns|mollusc, clam}}; so he proposes that the fifth earthly branch depicted the moon's second waning-gibbous phase, which looks like a clam. He also suggests that {{zh-l|辰}} also represented the ovoid-shaped rising sun and is thus related to {{zh-l|晨|early morning}}.

; “time”
: From {{och-l|時|time}} + nominalizing suffix ''-n'', literally “that which is proceeding” ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). This word partially converges with {{och-l|晨|morning}} ([[ibid.]]).

; “heavenly body”
: The endopassive of {{och-l|振|to shake; to stir}}, literally “to stir oneself”, i.e. “when life begins to stir” > “heavenly bodies that mark time” ([[ibid.]]).

